{{About|the theatre in Christchurch||Court Theatre (disambiguation)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=June 2014}} {{refimprove|date=November 2010}} [[File:Court Theatre - the shed.JPG|thumb|The current premises in [[Addington, New Zealand|Addington]]]] The '''Court Theatre''' is a professional theatre company based in [[Christchurch]], New Zealand. It was founded in 1971 and located in the [[Christchurch Arts Centre]] from 1976 until the February [[2011 Christchurch earthquake]]. It opened new premises in [[Addington, New Zealand|Addington]] in December 2011. It is currently New Zealand's largest theatre company and is led by CEO, [[Philip Aldridge]] and artistic director Ross Gumbley.
== History ==
===Founding and early years=== [[File:Canterbury Provincial Council Stone Chamber.jpg|thumb|Stone Chamber of the [[Canterbury Provincial Council Buildings|Canterbury Provincial Council]]]] The company was founded by Yvette Bromley {{post-nominals|country=NZL|QSM}} and [[Mervyn Thompson]] in 1971 who served as Co-artistic Directors for the first three years of the company.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.courttheatre.org.nz/index.cfm/1,9,html/About-Us | title=Christchurch's Theatre | publisher=Court Theatre | location=Christchurch | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724101856/http://www.courttheatre.org.nz/index.cfm/1%2C9%2Chtml/About-Us | archive-date=24 July 2011 | deadurl=yes | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Bromley chose the theatre's name out of affection for the [[Royal Court Theatre]] in [[London]], which she knew well from her upbringing and drama education.<ref name="ties to landmark" />
During the first eighteen months of its existence, The Court had three venues. The first was ''The Stone Chamber of the [[Canterbury Provincial Council Buildings|Canterbury Provincial Council Chambers]]'' (April – May 1971), where The Court's début production, ''The Prime of Miss Jean Brodie'' was staged.<ref name="ties to landmark">{{cite news |last1=Crean |first1=Mike |title=Reliving Court's ties to landmark |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/5833594/Reliving-Courts-ties-to-landmark |accessdate=15 August 2015 |work=[[The Press]] |date=22 October 2011 |page=C7}}</ref> Occasionally the [[Māori Land Court]] would require the use of the chamber, necessitating the set being struck and taken to the Durham Street Art Gallery; the furniture being moved back into the chamber and the processed reversed for the next evening's performance. The Stone Chamber was one of the city's most magnificent structures, but it was impractical for a theatre company, as there was little room for an audience and a lack of toilets.<ref name="ties to landmark" />
Next was the ''Durham Street Art Gallery'' (June 1971 – May 1972), which was used as an interim venue between the Canterbury Society of Arts vacating the premises and the Law Court expanding into the area.<ref name="ties to landmark" /> From June to August 1972, The Court was housed in the ''Beggs Theatrette'' and staged two productions in the space.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}}
The next four years (September 1972 – February 1976) were a period of relative stability. The Court Theatre was housed at The Orange Hall on Worcester Street. In 1974, Mervyn Thompson stood down leaving Yvette Bromley as sole Artistic Director until 1975 when Randall Wackrow (who had joined the company as Business Manager in 1973) joined her as Co-artistic Director.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}}
===The Arts Centre=== [[File:Court Theatre, Christchurch (Arts Centre).jpg|thumb|The Court Theatre at the [[Christchurch Arts Centre]]]] In 1976, the company moved to the [[Christchurch Arts Centre]] complex, in the buildings which were formerly the Engineering School of [[Canterbury College, Christchurch|Canterbury College]]. The performance space was previously lecture room D.<ref name="ties to landmark" />
From 1977 to 1978, Randall Wackrow served as sole Artistic Director, standing down in 1979 with the appointment of Elric Hooper.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}} Hooper served as Artistic Director for more than two decades.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}} Hooper declared his intent to balance the theatre's repertoire with "three main thrusts — the classic, the contemporary and the indigenous". Although economic pressure saw a fledgling second auditorium, ''Court Two'', closed as a regular venue following the economic slump of the mid-eighties (although it was to be later revived as ''The Forge''), overall this philosophy was rewarded.
As the new millennium approached, The Court saw growth across the board — in audiences, income and acclaim, and expanded its company with the introduction of [[Theatresports]] to [[Australasia]] in the late 1980s and the formation of professional improvisation troupe, [[Court Jesters|The Court Jesters]].{{citation needed|date=November 2010}} In 1990, Hooper was awarded the [[MBE]] and the 1990 Commemoration medal by the [[Queen Elizabeth II|Queen]].{{citation needed|date=November 2010}} Hooper retired as Artistic Director in 1999 and Catherine Downes served as Artistic Director of The Court Theatre from 2000–2005.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}} Ross Gumbley has been The Court's Artistic Director from 2006.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}}
