[[Image:Ny Carlsberg Glyptothek - Melpomene.jpg|thumb|Roman statue of Melpomene, 2nd century AD. The muse is shown in a long-sleeved garment with a high belt, clothing that was associated with tragic actors. Her wreath of vines and grapes alludes to [[Dionysus]], the god of the theatre.]]
[[File:Melpomene (by Joseph Fagnani).jpg|thumb|''Melpomene'' by [[Joseph Fagnani]] (1819–1873) (1869)]]

'''Melpomene''' ({{IPAc-en|m|ɛ|l|ˈ|p|ɒ|m|ᵻ|n|iː}}; {{lang-grc|[[wikt:Μελπομένη#Ancient Greek|Μελπομένη]]|Melpoménē|to sing' or 'the one that is melodious}}), initially the [[Muse]] of Chorus, she then became the '''Muse of Tragedy''', for which she is best known now.<ref>{{citation|last=Blyth |first=Charles |title=Virgilian Tragedy and [[Troilus]] |publisher= [[The Chaucer Review]] |date=1990 |volume=24 |number=3 |pages=211-218}}</ref> Her name was derived from the Greek verb melpô or melpomai meaning "to celebrate with dance and song." She is often represented with a tragic mask and wearing the [[cothurnus]], boots traditionally worn by tragic actors. Often, she also holds a knife or club in one hand and the tragic mask in the other.

Melpomene is the daughter of [[Zeus]] and [[Mnemosyne]]. Her sisters include [[Calliope]] (muse of epic poetry), [[Clio]] (muse of history), [[Euterpe]] (muse of lyrical poetry), [[Terpsichore]] (muse of dancing), [[Erato]] (muse of erotic poetry), [[Thalia (muse)|Thalia]] (muse of comedy), [[Polyhymnia]] (muse of hymns), and [[Urania]] (muse of astronomy).  She is also the mother of several of the [[Siren (mythology)#List of Sirens|Sirens]], the divine handmaidens of [[Persephone|Kore (Persephone/Proserpina)]] who were cursed by her mother, [[Demeter]]/[[Ceres (mythology)|Ceres]], when they were unable to prevent the kidnapping of Kore (Persephone/[[Proserpina]]) by [[Hades]]/[[Pluto (mythology)|Pluto]].  

In Roman and Greek poetry, it was traditional{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}} to invoke the goddess Melpomene so that one might create beautiful lyrical phrases (see [[Horace's Odes]]).

