[[File:Teatro Alfieri, Florence, design by Vittorio Bellini, 1828.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Vittorio Bellini's design for the 1828 renovation of the theatre]] The '''Teatro Alfieri''' was a major theatre and opera house in 18th and 19th century [[Florence]], located at Via dell'Ulivo #6 corner Via Pietrapiana in the [[Florence]], region of Tuscany, Italy.
==History== It was constructed originally in 1740 by members of the ''Accademia dei Risoluti''. At that time it was known as the ''Teatro di Santa Maria'' (the name of a nearby street) or the ''Teatro Risoluti''. The theatre underwent extensive reconstruction and enlargement in 1828, supervised by the architect [[Vittorio Bellini]] (1798 - 1860).<ref>Sistema Archivistico Nazionale. [http://www.san.beniculturali.it/web/san/dettaglio-soggetto-produttore?id=8578 "Bellini, Vittorio, architetto, (Firenze 1798 - 1860)"]. Retrieved 18 December 2013 {{it}}.</ref> It re-opened as the Teatro Alfieri, named in honour of the playwright [[Vittorio Alfieri]].
In its heyday, the theatre interior decorations were elaborate, was used for both prose drama and operas. In the late 19th century and early 20th centuries, it also became known as a performance venue for plays written in the [[Florentine dialect]]. The theatre was demolished in 1928 when the Fascist government of Florence re-developed the [[Basilica of Santa Croce, Florence|Santa Croce]] district.<ref>Garlington, p. 48</ref>
==Premieres== *''L'amore in guerra'', opera by [[Luigi Maria Viviani]], 8 February 1829<ref>*''Teatri, arti e letteratura'' (20 March 1829), [https://books.google.com/books?id=SMkqAAAAYAAJ "Spettacoli dello scorso carnevale"]. Anno 7, Numero 257, pp. 13–15 {{it}}.</ref><ref>Unless otherwise indicated, all items in this list are world premieres.</ref> *''Matilde a Toledo'', opera by [[Teodulo Mabellini]], 27 August 1836<ref name ="AA">{{Almanacco|match=Teatro Alfieri di Firenze}}</ref> *''Romilda e Ezzelino'', opera by [[Abramo Basevi]], 11 August 1840<ref name ="AA" /> *''Le educande di Sorrento'', opera by [[Emilio Usiglio]] 1 May 1868<ref name ="AA" /> *''Nozze sospirate'', opera by [[Oreste Carlini]], 10 January 1888<ref name ="AA" /> *''Una partita a scacchi'', opera by [[Enrico Ranfagni]], 13 February 1892<ref name ="AA" /> *''In congedo'', opera by [[Cesare Bacchini]], 1 October 1898<ref name ="AA" /> *''Sarrona'', opera by [[William Legrand Howland]], 3 February 1906 (Italian premiere)<ref>Hipsher, Edward Ellsworth (1927). [https://archive.org/details/americanopera030456mbp ''American Opera''], p. 270.</ref> *''L'acqua cheta'', play in Florentine dialect by [[Augusto Novelli]], 29 January 1908<ref name = "AdC">[[Accademia della Crusca]] (2003). [https://books.google.com/books?id=YTVdAAAAMAAJ&q=acqua+cheta+teatro+alfieri+29+January+1908&dq=acqua+cheta+teatro+alfieri+29+January+1908&hl=en&sa=X&ei=kHqxUuytFMWg7AbJp4DYCA&ved=0CEgQ6AEwAw ''Studi di grammatica italiana''] , p. 112.</ref> *''Il pateracchio'', play in Florentine dialect by [[Ferdinando Paolieri]], 2 February 1910<ref name = "AdC" />
